**Solution:**

We know that $\cos 60^\circ = \frac{1}{2}.$  Since the cosine function is even, $\cos (-60^\circ) = \frac{1}{2}$ as well.  The angle $-60^\circ$ is in the fourth quadrant, so its cosine is positive.  The angle in the second quadrant with cosine $-\frac{1}{2}$ is $-60^\circ + 180^\circ = 120^\circ.$  In radians, this is $120^\circ \cdot \frac{\pi}{180^\circ} = \boxed{\frac{2 \pi}{3}}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(120);
B = dir(240);
C = dir(0);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(O--A);
draw(O--B);
draw(O--C);

label("$\frac{2 \pi}{3}$", (O + A)/2, N);
label("$-\frac{1}{2}$", (O + B)/2, SW);
label("$\frac{1}{2}$", (O + C)/2, SE);
[/asy]
